<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Dante:
[I]Hi Lar, Hi All,

About AI in modern CRPGs, I think many important topics are already said, especially:
- the AI should never cheat (or it must never be apparant it does  :) )
- the AI should never be bviously "computer" stupid (NPC blocked in a corner, etc...)
But I am sure that the Larian Guys won't make these mistakes.

I am a fan of real life RPGs - played without computer and with a game master of any flavour. Compared to these games, what I lack in ALL CRPGs, even in Baldur's Gate (the word is out, sorry), is REAL intelligent interaction, and I mean especially outside battle time. I clarify:
1) battles should be fun and intelligent (as said in all other posts). Yes, it would be great that enemy mages hide behind their fighters instead of standing on the front row. Yes, it would be cool that monsters can be scared away instead of having them chopped in 1000 pieces every ##### time, over and over.
2) OUTSIDE battles, intelligent interaction with people is necessary:
- the blacksmith is sleeping at 2 AM in the morning so you can't buy new armor. Go to sleep first and return in the morning.
- if your reputation precedes you, people will react differently: (depending on that reputation and their own alignment) they will help you for free, refuse to give any information, sell goods cheap, ...
- great story elements are people who admire you so much that they sacrifice themselves to save you to allow your mission to be completed, or other people that follow you quite some time and then betray you, etc...

Although a lot of this belongs to the story line (and I have good hopes that it will be excellent according to the things you say), I think that you can do similar things in interactions that are not essential to the course of the story, based on the alignment and the courage/strength of the NPCs. Conflicting alignments (and alignment is defined by the sum of your actions) lead to unwillingness to cooperate or even to anger and battle (if courage/strength big enough compared to yours).

Examples:
- if you have a party of barbarian fighters, a (lawful good) paladin that you encounter will not be prepared to join forces.
- you enter the temple of good priests to heal your party members, but your group has a reputation of murdering innocent villagers. Sorry, they won't help you.
- let's say elves and dwarves are sworn enemies. You enter the elven village and your party exists of humans and one dwarf. It could be that you are rejected from the elven village, it could be that you are unwelcome, or it could be that no offense is taken because of the dwarven party member - all depending on your reputation.

Okay, I know implementing this requires A LOT of work in defining different dialogs depending on the situation, but hey, you strive to create a good RPG, and you asked the question...  :)[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
